		<div class="yearsago">This article was first published 10 years ago</div>		<div class="breadcrumb"><a href="https://www.rediff.com" class="bold">Home</a>&nbsp; &raquo;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.rediff.com/cricket" class="bold">Cricket</a> &raquo;&nbsp;3 Top reasons why ICC did not use 'Hotspot' as part of DRS</div>
		<h1 class="artihd">3 Top reasons why ICC did not use 'Hotspot' as part of DRS</h1>
		<div class="clearfix">
			<div class="floatL">
				<div class="bylinetop"></div>
				<div> </div>
			</div>
			<div class="floatR">Share:<a href="mailto:?subject=3%20Top%20reasons%20why%20ICC%20did%20not%20use%20%27Hotspot%27%20as%20part%20of%20DRS&body=Read this article https://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/icc-world-cup-3-top-reasons-why-did-not-use-hotspot-as-part-of-drs/20150213.htm" title="Share by Email" aria-label="Email Share"><i class="shareic_sprite email"></i></a><a target="_blank" OnClick="sharePopup(this);return false;" href="https://api.whatsapp.com/send?text=https://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/icc-world-cup-3-top-reasons-why-did-not-use-hotspot-as-part-of-drs/20150213.htm" title="Share on Whatsapp"  aria-label="Whatsapp Share"><i class="shareic_sprite waup"></i></a><a target="_blank" OnClick="sharePopup(this);return false;" href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/icc-world-cup-3-top-reasons-why-did-not-use-hotspot-as-part-of-drs/20150213.htm&text=3%20Top%20reasons%20why%20ICC%20did%20not%20use%20%27Hotspot%27%20as%20part%20of%20DRS"  title="Share on Twitter"  aria-label="Twitter Share"><i class="shareic_sprite twit"></i></a><a target="_blank" OnClick="sharePopup(this);return false;" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/icc-world-cup-3-top-reasons-why-did-not-use-hotspot-as-part-of-drs/20150213.htm&picture=&title=3%20Top%20reasons%20why%20ICC%20did%20not%20use%20%27Hotspot%27%20as%20part%20of%20DRS&description=" title="Share on Facebook"  aria-label="Facebook Share"><i class="shareic_sprite fb"></i></a><a target="_blank" OnClick="sharePopup(this);return false;" href="https://www.reddit.com/submit?url=https://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/icc-world-cup-3-top-reasons-why-did-not-use-hotspot-as-part-of-drs/20150213.htm&title=3%20Top%20reasons%20why%20ICC%20did%20not%20use%20%27Hotspot%27%20as%20part%20of%20DRS" title="Share on Reddit"  aria-label="Reddit Share"><i class="shareic_sprite reddit"></i></a>
			<p class="updatedon">February 13, 2015 14:47 IST</p>
			</div>
		</div>
				<div id="arti_content_n" class="arti_contentbig clearfix" itemprop="articleBody">
			<p><strong>The chief executive of the International Cricket Council (ICC) has defended the decision of not to use the Hotspot technology as part of the Decision Review System (DRS) during the World Cup, as he claims that it sometimes creates confusion.</strong></p><div id="div_morelike_topic_container"></div>
<p><span><img class=imgwidth  title="Indian supporters in the crowd hold up a sign about the DRS" src="//im.rediff.com/cricket/2015/feb/13drs.jpg?w=670&h=900" alt="Indian supporters in the crowd hold up a sign about the DRS" style="max-width:100%;"   /></span></p><div id="shop_advertise_div_1"></div><div class="clear"><div class="inline-block" id="div_arti_inline_advt"></div><div class="inline-block" id="div_arti_inline_advt2"></div></div>
<div style="padding: 5px; border: 1px solid #dfdfdf; clear: both; max-width: 670px; width: 99%;"><strong>Indian supporters in the crowd hold up a sign about the DRS. Photograph: Mark Kolbe/Getty Images</strong></div>
<p><span><span style="font-size: 36px;">1</span><strong>.</strong> The ICC have had plenty of fires to put out of late, but boss Dave Richardson has claimed that they've worked tirelessly to ensure the off field issues don't overshadow the cricket at the Cricket World Cup, one such being the Hotspot technology.</span></p>
<p><span><span style="font-size: 36px;">2</span>. Richardson claimed that the ICC were as well prepared as they've ever been to deal with corruption within the game as well as sledging, chucking, security and why Hotspot would not be used at the tournament starting on Saturday.</span></p>
<p><span>There are reportedly not enough of the cameras needed to use the Hotspot technology for the entire tournament, but it was offered for the knockout stages of the event. However, organisers opted not to use it for the seven knockout matches in favour of consistency.</span></p><div class="clear"></div><div class="advtcontainer lb"><div class="advttext"></div><div id="div_outstream_bottom"><ins data-revive-zoneid="391" data-revive-source="_blank" data-revive-target="_blank" data-revive-id="4b71f4079fb345c8ac958d0e9f0b56dd" data-zonename="Rediff_ROS_InArticleVideo_Middle_INTL"></ins></div></div><div class="clear"></div>
<p><span>Richardson</span><span> said that the vastly improved Real Time Snicko proved a really effective tool.</span></p>
<p><span><span style="font-size: 36px;">3</span>. The ICC boss revealed that Hotspot is brilliant when it comes to ball touching glove, but claimed that the faint edges on the bat sometimes it doesn't pick up and that can create confusion.</span></p>
<p><span>Richardson</span><span> said that with Real Time Snicko, he is confident that they would get all the edges. He said that it's much better than it was; the third umpire is able to watch a multi-screen shot with synchronised camera angles so when one sees the little graphic mark that Snicko makes, they would be able to see whether that mark occurs at the same time the ball is passing the bat.</span></p>
		</div>
		<div class="bylinebot">
																										<span class="ht10 clear"></span><div><i>AGENCIES</i></div>
